By now, #chia seed has be sung, praised, worshipped to ubiquity. But the prevalence canâ€™t diminish its awesomenessðŸŒŸ Itâ€™s high-fiber, high-protein, high-calcium and has good omega 3:6 ratio, among all the other goodies. 
And if youâ€™ve witnessed wonders that this tiny seed can creates, chia puddings, chia eggs, chia energy balls/granola bars/crackers, etc., know that it has one more trick up its sleeve...chia jam!! 
Iâ€™ve been wanting to give this a try for so long and finally did itâœŒðŸ?¼I donâ€™t even eat jams all that muchðŸ˜… Itâ€™s all because of chia seeds (The things we do forðŸ–¤) 
You can easily find dozens of recipes online. But for the sake of convenience, Iâ€™ll put it here. Itâ€™s super easy and takes less time than making a cup of coffeeðŸ˜‰ 

This makes about half a cup 
1 tbsp chia seeds
1 cup fresh or frozen fruit (I used fresh strawberries ðŸ?“ and frozen blueberries ðŸ«? this time)
about 1/2 tbsp lemon juice ðŸ?‹ 
about 1/2-1 tbsp maple syrup/coconut nectar, or any kind of sweetener

1. Over medium heat, stir the fruit in a small saucepan until it starts to bubble. Turn down the heat to simmer, mash it with a spatula/spoon.
2. Add the chia seeds until fully combined.
3. Take it off the stove. Let it cool a bit. The jam will continue to thicken as it cools.
4. Add the lemon juice and sweetener to your taste. Stir well. 
5. Eat now, or save the jam (once completely cools) in a sealed container and refrigerate.

The time has come for me to finally try these famous Next Level Meat Burgers !
Warning: if you don't like the look and taste of bovine meat, this burger could be shocking at first. It definitely looks like meat, both for the texture and the red beet juice , way too similar to blood so the imitation is uncanny. I found them easier to cook in the pan as they are extremely thick, not fragile and crumbly like other veg burgers can be sometimes, even though they require a bit more time (8-10 minutes approx to get uniformly done). Exactly like true meat burgers, they ooze greasy oil as you cook them( I didn't use any oil or butter just to see how they worked when grilled), and this could lead them to be more easily prone to get burnt so you need to stir them constantly. The taste is 95% meat. Champignon mushrooms and soy proteins definitely give them an ironish-fat aftertaste which resembles meat, but slightly bitter at the same time, which is the reason for the 5% missing because, despite the spices included,it tastes exactly like when the mince has not been salted enough, so I'd advise to add some salt, pepper or other spices while cooking if you feel the same. Anyway, it's an overall excellent product, very nutritive, and I'll definitely buy it again. 3â‚¬ at Lidl.
#nextlevelmeat #nextlevel #burgers

I love Banza's clear product labelling, as well as their use of #chickpeas which is wholesome, less food coma-inducing, and easier to cook to the right/desired texture ðŸ˜€

In case anyone's interested, here's the recipe for my cashew chutney (serves 3-4):
- 1 cup of cashew nuts
- 1 medium-sized garlic
- 4 medium-sized peppers (bell or chilli depending on your tastebuds)
- handfuls of tarragon, basil, and mint leaves
- cumin seeds
- cooking oil of choice (I used garlic-infused olive)
- 1 cup coconut milk yoghurt (I used half a cup so that's why it wasn't wet enough ðŸ˜•)

1. Soak the cashew nuts overnight
2. Cube the peppers and garlic. Toss in the olive oil, coat with the cumin seeds, and bake for 15-18 minutes at 180-200 degrees
3. Drain the cashews, toss in the mixed leaves and the cubed vegetables
4. Blend to desired fineness
5. Mix in coconut yoghurt and stir. Add olive oil if desired.

I baked something again lol. ðŸ?° This plum jam brings back childhood memories. Weâ€™ve always had it at home and itâ€™s simply delicious. Itâ€™s thick and creamy - this one even has some plum pieces inside. You can use it as a spread on bread rolls or bake something with it #veganrecipes #recipes I made cinnamon bread rolls with plum jam

1. Mix 10g of yeast with 100ml warm water. Add 2 tbsp sugar, 0.5 tsp salt, 2 tbsp oil and 240g flour. 
2. Knead the dough for five minutes and work the gluten! The dough shouldnâ€™t get too hard but should also not be runny. If you need to, add either some water or flour. 
3. Let the dough rise at a warm place for 30 min to two hours - until doubled in size. 
4. Press the dough down and let rise for 20 min again. 
5. In the meantime mix 2 tbsp with 1 tbsp of cinnamon 
6. Once the dough is done rising it should weight ~350g. I now separated it into 7 globs, each weighting 50g. Roll them into round shapes. 
7. Dip one side of each ball into the cinnamon-sugar mixture and put on a baking sheet lined with baking paper. 
8. Heat oven to 180Â°C 
9. Press a mould in the middle of each dough ball and add 1 tbsp of plum jam (or any other jam really)
10. Bake for 20 minutes and enjoy ðŸ˜Š

I use Slim Rice with everything. It is a great way to reduce carbs and create more calorie allowance for protein. It is not absorbent like normal rice, and technically it works better in the form of noodles or paste, as it is more similar in texture. However, the rice is more versatile, so I tend to stick to the rice. The only difference is the shape and colour. 

Be a little careful when first adding this to your diet, as it is extremely high in fibre, and can mess with your stomach if you are not used to a high fibre diet. Having said that, I have tried several types of konjac noodles, and this brand I found to be the least trouble-causing.  

When having with curry etc I tend to mix a 1/3 package with a little bit of rice and some oven baked cabbage rice, and that way I get the sauce absorption as well as the taste, and I can barely tell I'm eating a substitute. Saves money as well, win-win.

One huge minus is that there is so much packaging, both paper and plastic. Once a bag is opened, the product goes off within 48 hours, and it cannot be frozen, so it kind of has to be packaged in small portions.

I get this in bulk on subscription straight from the website, which saves quite a lot of money compared to buying single packets.

A definite recommend if you are a curd/yogurt person and are finding the going tough.

To put it simply - I would say it didn't meet my expectations. For those who are unfamiliar, Luncheon meat is pretty much like the queen of processed foods ðŸ˜‚ like Spam, Ham, etc. and is usually eaten as a whole piece or cubed.

I have 2 main "concerns" about this product.

1. I just feel like it didn't really have the classic Luncheon meat taste for the most part & that I've tasted wayyyy better vegan ones at a MUCH cheaper price point. Don't get me wrong, i think its good mock meat, just not a satisfying replacement for regular Luncheon meat.

2. The texture. I totally missed out on checking everyone's reviews. But DON'T THAW THESE! Because its a frozen product, I understand that it will loose its "binding" element slightly when defrosted. But I've definitely had ones where it's super easy to dice without them losing their shape. This one had more of a minced meat texture so after thawing at room temp for just a couple of minutes, it almost lost its shape when i lifted it off the packaging.

Also yes, i had to roll it into tiny meatballs bc it started falling into pieces ðŸ˜« There are 6 in a pack, which means I have 5 more tries to not thaw this & make the best of it, who knows, it might turn out so much better than i thought ðŸ’­
